\begin_layout Subsubsection
Adjusting for potential bias in the sample through reweighting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The purpose of this section is to test the implications of working with
 a biased sample.
 Specifically, samples that under-sample segments of the population.
 Re-weighting is applied by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "sinha2022poverty"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for the case of India where there were concerns regarding the sampling
 of the target survey.
 Although referred to by the authors as a max-entropy approach, the method
 used to adjust the target sample weights is in reality minimum cross-entropy
 where the sampling weights in the target survey are adjusted by the smallest
 extent possible given the constraints (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "wittenberg2010introduction"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
When the original sampling weights of the target survey are ignored, it
 is assumed that every observation had a similar probability of being selected,
 then the re-weighting method is max-entropy (see Golan, Judge and Miller
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "GolanBook"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for a more thorough exposition of maximum entropy).
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The constraints, in the case of India's imputation, correspond to the mean
 of a set of variables that are found in other nationally representative
 surveys.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Three possible adjustments for the covariate mismatch is proposed: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Covariate match
\series default
: The simple random sample’s mean of each covariate is used to calibrate
 the weights of the biased samples.
 For re-weighting, I use minimum cross-entropy to adjust prior weights by
 the smallest amount possible so that the constraints (i.e., the means) are
 satisfied.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Linear fit match
\series default
: The linear fit’s mean of the simple random sample is used to calibrate
 the weights of the biased samples.
 Weights are calibrated using minimum cross-entropy to adjust prior weights
 by the smallest amount possible so that the constraints (i.e., the means)
 are satisfied.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Linear fit & variance match
\series default
: The linear fit’s 
\series bold
mean
\series default
 and 
\series bold
variance
\series default
 of the simple random sample are used to calibrate the weights of the biased
 samples.
 Weights are calibrated using minimum cross-entropy to adjust prior weights
 by the smallest amount possible so that the constraints (i.e., the mean and
 the variance of the linear fit) are satisfied.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Since the simulated data does not have sampling weights, the priors are
 equal to 1 and thus minimum cross-entropy is in reality max-entropy in
 this instance.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Adjusting for potential bias in the sample through standardizing covariates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The basics of the method is simple.
 In principle, from the data where the model is fit (source data) the mean
 and variance of each covariate is known.
 Consequently, covariates in the sample to be imputed (target data) can
 be adjusted so that the mean and variance of the covariates are aligned
 to that of the source data.
 This is what 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "dang2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 recommend for making different survey samples more comparable.
 However, a key assumption here is that the covariates follow a normal distribut
ion.
 In tests done by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "dang2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 with data from Jordan the method is judged to be valid.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To test the validity of covariate standardization, the same samples detailed
 in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Extracting-samples"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Note, however, that the covariates here do not follow a normal distribution.
 Covariate standardization is done by adjusting the covariate from the 
\begin_inset Formula $new$
\end_inset

 survey in the follwoing manner:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{new}=(x_{new}-\hat{\mu}_{x_{new}})\frac{\hat{\sigma}_{x}}{\hat{\sigma}_{x_{new}}}+\hat{\mu}_{x}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following adjustments are considered:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Standardize each covariate: 
\series default
Every covairate in the model is standardize to ensure the mean and variance
 of each covariate in the biased samples matches those of the simple random
 sample.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Standardize the linear fit: 
\series default
The linear fit’s 
\series bold
mean
\series default
 and 
\series bold
variance
\series default
 of the simple random sample are used to standardize the linear fit in the
 biased samples.
 
\end_layout

