\begin_layout Subsection
Imputation over time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A key assumption when imputing across time is that the parameters are constant
 over time.
 This means that the relationship between the covariates and the dependent
 variable remain constant and that the distribution of the unobservables
 remain constant.
 In essence, the assumption is that any change in the welfare distribution
 will be entirely driven by changes in the covariates.
 Nevertheless, under variaous early work of S2S the common recommendation
 was to rely on covariates that are relatively stable and do not change
 (
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Add reference to papers
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
 Recommending the use of covariates that show minimal change is contradictory
 to the previous statement if the goal is to capture changes in poverty.
 In this section the discussion focuses on how changes in the parameters
 can affect the poverty predictions.
 In practice, it is possible that any of the parameters used for the imputation
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\beta,\:\sigma\right)$
\end_inset

 has changed over time, however it is impossible to know if changes compound
 or cancel eachother.
 
\end_layout

